Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @sweet potato{1} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender, ~{16-18%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @lime{1/2}.

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1} in a #sieve{}.

== Chicken Curry ==

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add the garlic and @pasanda style seasoning{1}. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{50%ml} to the chicken. Mix well, then add the lentils.

Bring to the boil, stir, then lower the heat so the sauce simmers gently.

Cook until the chicken is cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

== Finishing ==

Add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the curry a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the sweet potato is cooked, add to the curry with a squeeze of lime juice.

Taste and season if needed, adding a splash of water if it's a little dry.

== To Serve ==

Share the lentil and chicken curry between your #bowls{}.

Serve with any remaining lime cut into wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!